<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="R2-024" project="SprkChat Platform Enhancement R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Rate Limiting — Apply ADR-016 Limits to All New Phase 2 Endpoints</title>
    <status>pending</status>
    <phase>2</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, api, auth</tags>
    <estimated-effort>medium</estimated-effort>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>BFF API code implementation — applies ADR-016 rate limiting across all new Phase 2 endpoints; NFR-07 compliance; security hardening; depends on all Phase 2 endpoint tasks completing</rigor-reason>
    <dependencies>[010, 013, 014, 015, 022]</dependencies>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Apply ADR-016 rate limiting and concurrency bounds to all new endpoints and AI service calls
    introduced in Phase 2 of SprkChat R2.

    **Endpoints requiring rate limiting**:
    1. `POST /api/ai/chat/sessions/{sessionId}/documents` (upload, R2-013) — 5 uploads/min/user
    2. `POST /api/ai/chat/sessions/{sessionId}/documents/{documentId}/persist` (SPE persist, R2-014) — 20 req/min/user
    3. `POST /api/ai/chat/export/word` (Word export, R2-022) — 10 exports/min/user
    4. `POST /api/ai/playbooks/{playbookId}/index` (embedding trigger, R2-016) — 30 req/min (service-to-service, tenant-scoped)
    5. Chat streaming endpoint (R2-010) — verify existing rate limit is applied; adjust if needed

    **Concurrency bounds for AI service calls** (ADR-016 — no unbounded Task.WhenAll):
    1. Document Intelligence calls in `DocumentContextService` and upload endpoint — max 3 concurrent
    2. OpenAI embedding calls in `PlaybookDispatcher` and `PlaybookIndexingService` — max 5 concurrent
    3. Bing Web Search calls in `WebSearchTools` — max 2 concurrent (already added in R2-017, verify)
    4. AI Search queries in `PlaybookDispatcher` — max 10 concurrent

    **Error response format** (ADR-001 + ADR-019):
    - Rate limit exceeded: `429 Too Many Requests` with `Retry-After: {seconds}` header and ProblemDetails body:
      ```json
      { "type": "...", "title": "Too Many Requests", "status": 429,
        "detail": "Rate limit exceeded. Retry after {N} seconds." }
      ```
    - AI service overloaded/unavailable: `503 Service Unavailable` with ProblemDetails body

    **Implementation approach**:
    - Verify that each new endpoint has a rate limit policy applied via endpoint filter or attribute
    - For endpoints where rate limiting was added inline (e.g., in R2-013), verify correctness
    - For any endpoint missing rate limiting, add it now
    - Check that all `SemaphoreSlim` bounded concurrency guards are in place for AI service calls
    - Run `dotnet test` to verify no regressions
  </prompt>

  <role>Senior .NET developer with Azure AI and Minimal API expertise</role>

  <goal>
    All Phase 2 endpoints return `429 Too Many Requests` with ProblemDetails when rate limits are
    exceeded. All AI service call sites use bounded concurrency (SemaphoreSlim or equivalent).
    No unbounded `Task.WhenAll` on AI service calls exists in the codebase. NFR-07 compliance verified.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="Project specification — NFR-07 (rate limiting all AI endpoints), ADR-016 constraints">projects/ai-sprk-chat-platform-enhancement-r2/spec.md</file>
    <file purpose="Project AI context — rate limiting requirements, ProblemDetails format">projects/ai-sprk-chat-platform-enhancement-r2/CLAUDE.md</file>
    <file purpose="ADR-016 — rate limiting requirements, concurrency bounds, error response format">../.claude/adr/ADR-016-ai-rate-limits.md</file>
    <file purpose="All new Phase 2 endpoint files for audit">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/</file>
    <file purpose="All new Phase 2 service files with AI calls for concurrency audit">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/</file>
    <file purpose="Endpoint filters pattern — how rate limiting is applied to Minimal API endpoints">../.claude/patterns/api/endpoint-filters.md</file>
  </inputs>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-016">ALL AI endpoint calls MUST be rate-limited — NFR-07 states no exceptions; each endpoint type has its own limit based on expected load</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-016">MUST NOT allow unbounded Task.WhenAll on AI service calls — SemaphoreSlim with documented max concurrency is required at each call site</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-001">Rate limit error responses MUST use ProblemDetails format with `Retry-After` header — MUST NOT return plain text or HTML error responses</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-019">All error responses MUST use ProblemDetails (RFC 7807) — `type`, `title`, `status`, `detail` fields required</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec NFR-07">ALL AI endpoint calls must be rate-limited — this is non-negotiable for the R2 release</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/ai-sprk-chat-platform-enhancement-r2/spec.md</file>
      <file>projects/ai-sprk-chat-platform-enhancement-r2/CLAUDE.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ChatEndpoints.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ChatDocumentEndpoints.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ChatWordExportEndpoints.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/DocumentContextService.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/PlaybookDispatcher.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Indexing/PlaybookIndexingService.cs</file>
      <file>.claude/patterns/api/endpoint-filters.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-016-ai-rate-limits.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-001-minimal-api.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-019-problemdetails.md</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern>Rate limit endpoint filter: check existing rate limiting infrastructure in the BFF — there should be a `RateLimitingFilter` or similar already; apply it to new endpoints with per-endpoint limit configuration</pattern>
      <pattern>429 response with Retry-After: `context.Response.Headers["Retry-After"] = retryAfterSeconds.ToString(); return TypedResults.Problem("Rate limit exceeded...", statusCode: 429, title: "Too Many Requests")`</pattern>
      <pattern>Concurrency audit: search for `Task.WhenAll` in Services/Ai/ — any unbounded use must be replaced with SemaphoreSlim or bounded parallel execution</pattern>
      <pattern>503 for overloaded upstream: catch `HttpRequestException` or specific Azure SDK exceptions from AI services; return `TypedResults.Problem("AI service temporarily unavailable", statusCode: 503)` with Retry-After header</pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Each Phase 2 task was asked to add rate limiting inline as part of its implementation.
      This task serves as a consolidation and verification pass to ensure:
      1. Every new endpoint actually has rate limiting (some tasks may have deferred it)
      2. All AI service call sites have concurrency bounds
      3. Error response formats are consistent with ADR-001/ADR-019 across all new endpoints
      4. No `Task.WhenAll` unbounded calls were introduced

      This is NOT a performance optimization task — it's a compliance task. ADR-016 is a hard
      requirement for the R2 release. The task should be primarily additive (filling gaps) with
      minimal changes to working code from other tasks.

      The 429/503 error response format must be consistent: every AI endpoint in the BFF should
      return the same ProblemDetails JSON structure for rate limit and overload errors. This is
      also important for the frontend error handling (Phase 3 tasks expect specific error shapes).
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      Depends on Tasks R2-010, R2-013, R2-014, R2-015, R2-022 (the major endpoint implementation tasks).
      Also benefits from R2-016, R2-017, R2-019, R2-021, R2-023 being complete (more complete audit).
      Sequential. Last implementation task before R2-025 (deployment). Own files: potential changes
      across all new endpoint and service files from Phase 2 (read-heavy, targeted additions only).
    </dependencies>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0">Read `ADR-016-ai-rate-limits.md` to confirm the required rate limits per endpoint type and concurrency bounds per AI service</step>
    <step order="1">Audit all new endpoint files from Phase 2 (`ChatDocumentEndpoints.cs`, `ChatWordExportEndpoints.cs`, playbook index endpoint) — check for rate limit filter application</step>
    <step order="2">For each endpoint missing rate limiting: add the appropriate rate limit filter/policy following the existing BFF rate limiting pattern</step>
    <step order="3">Add `Retry-After` header to all 429 responses from rate-limited endpoints</step>
    <step order="4">Search for `Task.WhenAll` in `Services/Ai/` — verify each usage is bounded (SemaphoreSlim or explicit max concurrency)</step>
    <step order="5">Audit `DocumentContextService.cs` (multi-document parallel retrieval): verify SemaphoreSlim max=5 is in place</step>
    <step order="6">Audit `PlaybookDispatcher.cs`: verify bounded concurrency for AI Search and embedding calls</step>
    <step order="7">Audit `PlaybookIndexingService.cs`: verify bounded embedding generation calls</step>
    <step order="8">Verify `WebSearchTools.cs` has SemaphoreSlim max=2 (from R2-017)</step>
    <step order="9">Standardize 503 response format for upstream AI service failures across all new services</step>
    <step order="10">Run `dotnet build` — verify no errors</step>
    <step order="11">Run `dotnet test` — verify no regressions from rate limiting additions</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task R2-024 status to completed (🔲 → ✅)</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>dotnet</tool>
    <tool>git</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <artifact type="code">Various Phase 2 endpoint and service files — targeted additions of rate limit policies, Retry-After headers, SemaphoreSlim guards, and 503 error handling where missing</artifact>
    <artifact type="docs">notes/024-rate-limiting-audit.md — audit checklist documenting which endpoints have which limits and which concurrency guards are in place</artifact>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">All five listed endpoint types return `429 Too Many Requests` with `Retry-After` header when rate limits are exceeded</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">All 429 responses include a ProblemDetails JSON body with `status: 429`, `title: "Too Many Requests"`, and `detail` with retry information</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No unbounded `Task.WhenAll` exists in `Services/Ai/` (grep audit passes)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document Intelligence calls are bounded at max 3 concurrent</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">OpenAI embedding calls are bounded at max 5 concurrent</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Bing Web Search calls are bounded at max 2 concurrent</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When Azure OpenAI is unavailable, affected endpoints return `503 Service Unavailable` with ProblemDetails (not an unhandled 500)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` and `dotnet test` both pass with no errors or new failures</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    Rate limiting implementation in .NET Minimal API can be done via:
    1. ASP.NET Core built-in rate limiting middleware (`AddRateLimiter` + `RequireRateLimiting`)
    2. Custom endpoint filters
    3. Third-party libraries already in use in the project

    Check what rate limiting approach is already used for existing endpoints before introducing
    a new pattern. Consistency is more important than "best" approach.

    The concurrency bounds are defensive programming against runaway AI service costs. For the
    embedding service, 5 concurrent is generous — production may warrant lower values. Document
    the chosen values and their rationale in `notes/024-rate-limiting-audit.md`.

    If the existing BFF has an `AiRateLimitingOptions` or similar configuration class, add the
    new endpoint limits to it rather than hardcoding numbers. This enables configuration-time
    tuning without code changes.
  </notes>

  <execution>
    <skill>.claude/skills/task-execute/SKILL.md</skill>
    <protocol>Phase 2 Sequential — depends on R2-010, R2-013, R2-014, R2-015, R2-022 at minimum. Should be the last BFF implementation task before R2-025 deployment. Run `dotnet test` in addition to `dotnet build` to verify no regressions. Own scope: targeted additions across multiple Phase 2 files.</protocol>
  </execution>
</task>
